															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2203795&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203737" alt="Kalinin" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2203795)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;" >Kalinin</a></span> <span class="odate time_1437412844 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 Jul 2015 17:20</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2341875">
									

<blockquote>
<p>Do that many people really read stuff exclusively on a cellphone? This is an honest question, because it really doesn't strike me as something one needs to go out of their way to accommodate.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><a href="http://marketingland.com/nielsen-time-accessing-internet-smartphones-pcs-73683" target="_blank">This</a> Nielsen study from early 2014 states that people spend an average of 34 hours per month on the internet via smartphone, compared to an average of 27 hours of PC-based internet usage. That proportion is unlikely to have tipped in favor of PCs in the last year and a half.</p>
<p>People don't generally use the internet exclusively from their phones. But the data indicates that most internet usage is mobile now. So yes, we should probably at least consider the mobile experience when we write stuff. People forget a lot of the time that ultimately we're writing for readers. Beyond that, are we really going to argue about the necessity of considering the use of smartphones?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>After all, you can't view high resolution images or play high-end games on a cellphone, either, and no one says they should stop making those.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That would make some sort of sense if that was what we did here. Except we don't. We are not purveyors of video games or a clearinghouse of high-resolution imagery. We offer writing. If there is anything that should be accessible from a mobile device, it should be writing. I'm not saying that mobile accessibility should be the only factor to consider when writing a piece, but we're well past the point now where we need to accept that phones are going to be most likely the majority of the devices used to access the site. Authors should not be surprised at downvotes and criticism for failing to take that into account by now.</p>

							</div>

								
					
