															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203737" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1437291411 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Jul 2015 07:36</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2340993">
									

<p>For a first post, this is incredibly ambitious, and I like it a lot. (+1)</p>
<p>The language is rather informal/vulgar. It's a little grating, but I think that's just because the first orientations were written back in Lolfondaution days and that's where you're pulling your inspiration. I can't criticize you too hard because I did it as well.</p>
<p>The full content is absolutely not going to be for people new to the wiki who don't know all the formatting tricks, which is unfortunate. I upvoted for the multiple layered story-threads in the hidden text, which I found rather interesting and a mostly unfamiliar take on the canon. In the interest of the new readers, I'm going to go back and try to review it visible-text-only.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>- As Scantron said, the quotation marks are completely unnecessary and contribute to some weird breaks in the text. It's especially strange because some of your rollovers have quotations and some do not.</p>
<p>- Some of the splits you make to make it easier for people to read rollovers are rather awkward in plain-text. For example,</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Question?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>would probably look clearer if you moved some portion of</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;I'm Junior Researcher Zack Sine, and, I, ah, yes?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>onto the line with it.</p>
<p>- Similarly, it's an incredibly awkward leap from</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;But today, I'm going to be completely honest with you.&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>to</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Which gets us to the important part&#8230;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>If you put it together as a sentence, you'd get something like &quot;But today I'm going to be completely honest with you, which gets us to the important part: you don't have to worry about us secretly feeding you drugs.&quot; It looks less weird together, but the grammar is still wonky. With the first part separated into a rollover chunk, it magnifies the oddness.</p>
<p>- Back to point 1,</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Well first [REDACTED]</p>
</blockquote>
<p>looks just plain weird with one quotation mark. Eliminating those would help that.</p>
<p>- The [REDACTED] bar is ok for indicating that time has passed, but the last paragraph beginning with &quot;Look at the time&quot; implies that there has been a second time gap. There's nothing indicating that that was the case except the odd-looking two-line break, which also disrupts the flow. Maybe a &quot;&#8230;&quot; a line before the hidden collapsible?</p>
<p>- The footnote section is still visible in plain-text. It's possible for plain-texters to figure out that you can highlight that, and I think the footnote text is mostly acceptable out-of-context and could serve as a suggestion that there is more hidden, but it still looks kind of odd.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>As for the additional story elements, I like layer 2-ish (overambitious memesters) and layer 3-ish (new-world collective), although as a rule I hate 0-point text, since the only place I know you can find it is in page source.</p>
<p>I like to imagine that these people, much like the rest of the Foundation, are perennially unaware of the <a href="/we-need-to-talk-about-fifty-five">Antimemetics Division</a> and probably in pretty regular conflict with them.</p>
<p>Edit: Also, what was the change in the gif? I tried to split it up, but that's a lot of frames :(</p>

							</div>

								
