				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2203795&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203737" alt="Kalinin" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2203795)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;" >Kalinin</a></span> <span class="odate time_1437293231 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Jul 2015 08:07</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2341005">
									

<p>This has all the issues that are inherent to these &quot;Orientation to [insert division here]&quot; tales. Typically, they're less a story of any sort than a piece of single-serve worldbuilding, delivered directly to the reader, usually in the form of a wise-cracking, irreverent researcher who inevitably talks as though they were about 19 years old. They come across, more than anything, as a harangue in favor of a particular interpretation of the Foundation, not a story that as a reader I'm really interested in following. I'm not generally in favor of someone telling me how it is. Tell me what <em>happens.</em></p>
<p>I'll be charitable and assume that the multiple layers of format fuckery are a genuine attempt to create interest and not an attempt to paper over some of the weaknesses of the trope that you're employing here. But the fact still remains that you seem to be aware of the fact that this is thin as is, and that it needed some bells and whistles added into it. The problem with that is that if you don't have a solid reason for the reader to stick around, the bells and whistles tend to serve as distractions, rather than something that draws a reader in deeper.</p>
<p>As far as I can tell, for all of its attempts at intricacy, this doesn't even really touch the nature of a cognitohazard or an anomalous meme. It's a laundry list of mystical references stewed together until I'm left with the impression that what I'm looking at isn't actually a scientific attempt to understand an anomaly or any sort of grappling with the implications that there is shit out there that can do things just by someone knowing about them. To be kind of glib, the end product I see here is &quot;you're a wizard, Harry&quot; run through some overly detailed occult filters.</p>
<p>This is evidently succeeding, but on a personal level, I don't really see a whole lot here. I feel like I've been assaulted with smoke and mirrors and then led into an empty room where nothing is happening. I cannot support a piece like that being on the wiki.</p>

							</div>

								
					
